7. eldritch.lua: eldritch.nvim is the main theme and it's already covered in the plugin strategy under nixpkgs vimPlugins, so that's accounted for.

The user might not have noticed it in the plan, or they're pointing out that it's not clearly listed in the plugin files themselves. Let me systematically check what's actually covered across all the plugin files versus what's in the strategy to see if there's a gap. Continuing through the plugin checklist, I'm verifying helpview.nvim, nvim-highlight-colors, inc-rename.nvim, and the kitty-related plugins are all accounted for. The lsp.lua configuration has most dependencies mapped out, though mason and its related tools still need migration. Moving on to lualine.lua next. I'm finishing up the plugin configuration files—snacks.nvim completes, then moving through snippets, treesitter, whichkey, and yanky with their respective dependencies all accounted for. Now I'm double-checking the lsp.lua file to make sure I haven't overlooked any plugins, verifying that vim-illuminate, nvim-lspconfig, and mason.nvim are all tracked.

I've confirmed the remaining lsp plugins like trouble.nvim, lazydev.nvim, rustaceanvim, clangd_extensions, tiny-inline-diagnostic, and lspkind are all in the plan, plus blink-copilot from blink.lua. The key thing I need to clarify is that eldritch.nvim is already accounted for under the theme plugin, even though it might not be immediately obvious to the user. I'm checking whether eldritch is available as a colorscheme in nixvim, since I've seen other popular themes like catppuccin and tokyonight listed there already.*

